Jacob Zuma's lawyers have told the High Court in Pietermaritzburg that the former president should not be made to suffer because of what they say are trumped-up charges. Advocate Thabani Masuku argued the corruption case is entirely cooked-up. Courtesy #DStv403 #eNCA JOHANNESBURG - Judgment in former president Jacob Zuma's latest attempt to have State Prosecutor, Billy Downer removed from his corruption trial, is expected on 16 February. Jacob Zuma's lawyers have told the High Court in Pietermaritzburg that the former president shouldn't be made to suffer because of what they say are trumped-up charges. Advocate Thabani Masuku argued the corruption case is entirely cooked-up. READ | Zuma in fresh bid to drop graft trial prosecutor Claims of misconduct by Zuma against the state were strengthened, by allegations made by former Asset Forfeiture Unit Head Willie Hofmeyr. In his affidavit, he says it was clear, decisions about this case were being made from elsewhere. Advocate Andrew Breitenbach says Zuma has no right to seek to leave to appeal until he has been convicted and sentenced. Breitenbach says it is in the interest of justice for an appeal to wait until the end of the trial. Watch the video above for more details on this story.